Well, this answer is late, but nonetheless here it is:<br><br>
I agree, and never truly compared my experience in the gulf to that of Viet Nam.  At first I was a bit stung by what you said, but here goes.<br><br>
First, I spent a total of about 14 months over there.  Second, the war everyone saw on TV was not the average war there.  Only the pilots and the airdales saw that war.  <br><br>
In fact, I did not see a tremendous amount of combat, but as a medic I saw more than enough of the end result of it.  I believe a lot of the problems coming out of it was due to my father and his problems post war, and being asked as a humanitarian to do things that were beyond the scope of my beliefs (and sometimes the Geneva Convention)<br><br>
You can call me yellow, or what you want but the reason I was a medic was to possibly save lives, not take them, or neglect them as the case more often was.<br><br>
Perhaps you took my statements out of context of the original conversation as muchg was discussed there..  I was merely postulating that maybe a combination of the two played a role in my actions and psyche after the war.<br><br>
As far as &quot;outside the realm of human emotion&quot; I think the job of being a medic assigned not only to take care of our casualties (which were far more than overturned jeeps as I believed you called it) and the Iraqi casualties could very well be deemed beyond the scope.  Burns, amputations, blown off limbs etc....  <br><br>
An old priest once told me &quot;never compare the size of your cross you bear to someone else's, his may only be 2 feet by two feet and yours 6X6, but his may be made of pure lead and yours wood.&quot;  I would never say that I experienced anything close to what the Viet Nam vets did, but I saw what I saw, and I feel what I feel.<br>

<p><code>--   (T. Adams) </code><p>


